  <article class="prose">
    <header class="page-head">
      <h1>About</h1>
    </header>

    <h2>What is lattice technology?</h2>
    <p>
      A <em>lattice</em> is a mathematical structure in which any two elements
      have a well-defined join (least upper bound). Applied to distributed
      systems, lattices let independent actors merge their state
      deterministically, without coordination, locks, or central authority,
      and always arrive at the same result.
    </p>
    <p>
      Lattice-based networks store, execute, and persist code and data across
      many peers, with state that converges by construction. This makes them a
      strong foundation for federated systems, digital assets, shared execution
      environments, and cross-organisational collaboration.
    </p>

    <h2>What you'll find here</h2>
    <p>
      This site provides a navigable index of the lattice
      ecosystem covering platforms, SDKs, MCP servers, developer tools, apps,
      documentation, and the organisations building with them. Every entry
      links straight to the source.
    </p>
    <p>
      Built for developers, researchers, and organisations exploring
      lattice-based systems.
    </p>

    <h2>Contributing</h2>
    <p>
      Missing something? Suggest additions or corrections via
      <a href="https://github.com/brittleboye/awesome-lattice/issues" rel="noopener">GitHub issues</a>
      or open a pull request.
    </p>
  </article>
